r(edges2)\n        return max(d1, d2, (d1 + 1) // 2 + (d2 + 1) // 2 + 1)\n\n    def treeDiameter(self, edges: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        def dfs(i: int, fa: int, t: int):\n            for j in g[i]:\n                if j != fa:\n                    dfs(j, i, t + 1)\n            nonlocal ans, a\n            if ans < t:\n                ans = t\n                a = i\n\n        g = defaultdict(list)\n        for a, b in edges:\n            g[a].append(b)\n            g[b].append(a)\n        ans = a = 0\n        dfs(0, -1, 0)\n        dfs(a, -1, 0)\n        return ans\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Tree Diameter Calculation**:\n   - The `treeDiameter` function calculates the diameter of a given tree.\n   - It uses two depth-first searches (DFS). The first DFS finds the farthest node from an arbitrary starting node, and the second DFS calculates the distance from this farthest node to all other nodes to find the longest path (diameter).\n\n2. **Combining Two Trees**:\n   - The `minimumDiameterAfterMerge` function calculates the diameter of the two separate trees using the `treeDiameter` function.\n   - It then calculates the potential new diameter if the two trees are connected by an edge between any two nodes from each tree.\n   - The formula `(d1 + 1) // 2 + (d2 + 1) // 2 + 1` computes the maximum possible diameter when connecting the two trees. Here, `(d1 + 1) // 2` and `(d2 + 1) // 2` represent the longest half-path in each tree plus one (to account for the connecting edge).\n\n3. **Result**:\n   - The function returns the maximum value among the diameters of the individual trees and the potential new diameter after merging them.", "estimated_date": 1719705600000}